Multi Checkbox

In this challenge, you'll build a MultiCheckbox component which allows the user to click and drag to check/uncheck multiple checkboxes:

Difficulty

This challenge is way trickier than I was originally expecting it to be. There are lots of little gotchas with this one.

Rules

  • Immer has been installed in this playground, if you wish to use it. Otherwise, no third-party libraries are allowed.
  • Feel free to google anything you'd like.

Playground

Code Playground

/*
Acceptance Criteria:

• The `MultiCheckbox` component should be made into a generic, reusable component.
• Clicking and dragging on a checkbox should toggle all checkboxes, until the left mouse button is released.
• The user shouldn't have to hover over the checkbox specifically. The label should also trigger this effect.
• When mousing over checkboxes, they should all be toggled in the same direction (either all toggled on, or all toggled off).
• The checkboxes should work normally for keyboard users. Focusing and hitting the "Space" key should toggle the checkbox.
• Don't worry about mobile / touchscreen inputs. In practice, this is something we'd want to solve for, but the playground doesn't make it easy to test touch events.
*/

import React from 'react';

import MultiCheckbox from './MultiCheckbox';

const DAYS = [
{ label: 'Monday', value: 'monday' },
{ label: 'Tuesday', value: 'tuesday' },
{ label: 'Wednesday', value: 'wednesday' },
{ label: 'Thursday', value: 'thursday' },
{ label: 'Friday', value: 'friday' },
{ label: 'Saturday', value: 'saturday' },
{ label: 'Sunday', value: 'sunday' },
];

function App() {
return (
<>
<h1>Foodorama Order Form</h1>
<p>
Sign up to receive daily meal delivery service.
</p>
<form>
<h2>
Select days:
</h2>
<MultiCheckbox options={DAYS} />
<button>
Confirm Order
</button>
</form>
<footer>
Copyright Foodorama. All Rights Reserved.
</footer>
</>
)
}

export default App;

Inside the MultiCheckbox component, we have a hardcoded set of days. This isn't ideal; instead, we should be using the options prop to dynamically render a list item for each option.

Check out the “Mapping Over Data” lesson from Module 1 if you need a quick refresher on how to do this.

In order for the multi-select gesture to work, we need to be controlling the checkboxes with React state.

The Input Cheatsheet has an example of how to work with multiple controlled checkboxes.

Typically, checkboxes are checked and unchecked using the onChange event, which is timed to the "mouseup" event. The user has to click and release the mouse button to toggle the checkbox.

This doesn't work for us, in this particular use case.

Instead, let's remove the onChange event, and instead use onMouseDown. We can move the onMouseDown event to the parent <li>, so that it fires whether the user clicks the checkbox or the label.

NOTE: This will break the experience for keyboard users, so you'll need to come up with an alternative for them.

For the main interaction, you can listen for onMouseEnter events, to tell when the user has moused over a particular checkbox.

You'll want to track whether the user currently has the mouse depressed, to decide whether to toggle the checkbox or not. You can do this either by tracking it with a state variable, or by using the event.buttons property.

If you toggle each checkbox to its opposite value when the user uses the multi-select gesture, you'll get weird stuff like this:

Instead, we want to track the current “selecting mode”, based on the value of the first checkbox that was toggled:

  • If we're checking that first checkbox, then all hovered checkboxes should also become checked.
  • If we're unchecking that first checkbox, then all hovered checkboxes should also become unchecked.

To restore functionality for keyboard users, we can listen for the onKeyDown event on the checkboxes. If the user presses the "Space" key when focusing a checkbox, that checkbox should be toggled.

Attempt code (success)

I forgot to fix the key warning in my attempt video! This has been fixed in the code below.

// App.js
import React from 'react';


import MultiCheckbox from './MultiCheckbox';


const DAYS = [
  { label: 'Monday', value: 'monday' },
  { label: 'Tuesday', value: 'tuesday' },
  { label: 'Wednesday', value: 'wednesday' },
  { label: 'Thursday', value: 'thursday' },
  { label: 'Friday', value: 'friday' },
  { label: 'Saturday', value: 'saturday' },
  { label: 'Sunday', value: 'sunday' },
];


function App() {
  const [selectedDays, setSelectedDays] = React.useState({});


  function handleToggle(value, nextChecked) {
    setSelectedDays({
      ...selectedDays,
      [value]:
        typeof nextChecked === 'boolean'
          ? nextChecked
          : !selectedDays[value],
    });
  }


  return (
    <>
      <h1>Foodorama Order Form</h1>
      <p>Sign up to receive daily meal delivery service.</p>
      <form>
        <h2>Select days:</h2>
        <MultiCheckbox
          options={DAYS}
          selectedValues={selectedDays}
          handleToggle={handleToggle}
        />


        <button>Confirm Order</button>
      </form>
      <footer>Copyright Foodorama. All Rights Reserved.</footer>
    </>
  );
}


export default App;
// MultiCheckbox.js
import React from 'react';


import styles from './MultiCheckbox.module.css';


function MultiCheckbox({ options, selectedValues, handleToggle }) {
  const id = React.useId();
  // true | false | null
  const [selectingMode, setSelectingMode] = React.useState(false);


  React.useEffect(() => {
    if (typeof selectingMode !== 'boolean') {
      return;
    }


    function handleMouseUp() {
      setSelectingMode(null);
    }


    window.addEventListener('mouseup', handleMouseUp);


    return () => {
      window.removeEventListener('mouseup', handleMouseUp);
    };
  }, [selectingMode]);


  return (
    <ol className={styles.wrapper}>
      {options.map(({ label, value }) => {
        const optionId = `multi-checkbox-${value}-${id}`;
        const currentChecked = !!selectedValues[value];
        const nextChecked = !currentChecked;


        return (
          <li
            key={value}
            className={styles.option}
            onMouseDown={() => {
              handleToggle(value);
              setSelectingMode(nextChecked);
            }}
            onMouseEnter={() => {
              if (selectingMode === null) {
                return;
              }
              handleToggle(value, selectingMode);
            }}
          >
            <input
              type="checkbox"
              id={optionId}
              value={value}
              checked={currentChecked}
              onKeyDown={(event) => {
                if (event.code === 'Space') {
                  handleToggle(value);
                }
              }}
            />
            <label htmlFor={optionId}>{label}</label>
          </li>
        );
      })}
    </ol>
  );
}


export default MultiCheckbox;
Don't actually do this (warning)

I chose this challenge because it touches on lots of complex ideas, but honestly, I don't think we actually want to do things like this in real apps.

I'm always very wary when it comes to changing the default input modalities for form controls. People expect checkboxes to work in certain ways, and by not using onChange, we may be subtly breaking conventions we don't even know about.

If you do want to implement something like this, please do lots of additional testing to make sure you haven't accidentally broken the experience in some way.
